{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490891"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:20:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/774"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.09,0.07,0.58,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52725"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/774"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38093"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"3836"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8149"},{"type":"tags","id":"8151"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35474"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52725"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents with a two week history of dull pain in her right hip. Movement does not make the pain better or worse. Seven years earlier she underwent a mastectomy and axillary clearance for a 2cm, node positive, oestrogen receptor positive breast cancer. She received adjuvant systemic chemotherapy and tamoxifen for five years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe physical examination is unremarkable. Imaging confirms the presence of an isolated bony metastasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Letrozole","Denosumab","Surgical intervention","Radiotherapy","Restart chemotherapy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Eis the best option in this scenario because it can target the isolated bony metastasis specifically, reducing pain and preserving function in the affected joint. Radiotherapy can deliver a high dose of radiation to the lesion while minimizing exposure to healthy tissue. It is a highly effective and well-tolerated treatment for bony metastases in breast cancer, and it is often recommended as a first-line treatment for patients with breast cancer that presents with bony metastasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHormonal therapy is usually considered second-line treatment. \u003Cstrong\u003ELetrozole\u003C/strong\u003E is an example of this and is useful to treat hormone receptor-positive breast cancer by blocking and lowering the amount of estrogen. These therapies are particularly useful to reduce the risk of recurrence. As this patient already has a recurrence, it would not be useful in treating the bony mets but could be considered in the future to prevent further metastasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be a useful treatment for metastasis. There are many potential side effects as chemotherapy is a systemic treatment. It may be recommended if cancer is rapidly growing, not responsive to other treatments or there is a significant amount of cancer in other organs such as the liver or lungs. As this metastasis is isolated, it is not suggested that chemotherapy would be the best first-line therapy. Further, as the patient has already undergone chemotherapy, continuing the same treatment may not be as effective as a new treatment option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDenosumab \u003C/strong\u003Emay be given with the aim to relieve pain and reduce the risk of pathological fracture by inhibiting the action of osteoclasts. Whilst this is likely to be a component of the patient\u0027s ongoing treatment, it is not the most appropriate treatment initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical intervention\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate initial treatment for an isolated bony metastasis. It is typically reserved for specific cases where surgery can provide significant benefits, such as an impending fracture or spinal cord compression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radiotherapy is an effective option for isolated bony metastases in breast cancer, targeting bony lesion with minimal exposure to healthy tissue."],"references":["Katayama N, Katsiu K, Watanabe K, et al. Radiation therapy for oligometastatic bone disease in breast cancer. Translational Cancer Research. 2020;9(8). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8797907/","Role of Bone-Modifying Agents in Metastatic Breast Cancer: An American Society of Clinical Oncology\u2013Cancer Care Ontario Focused Guideline Update. Journal Of Clinical Oncology. 2017;35(35):3978-3986. Available at: https://ascopubs.org/doi/10.1200/JCO.2017.75.4614","Garmatls CJ, Chu FC. The effectiveness of radiation therapy in the treatment of bone metastases from breast cancer. Radiology. 1978;126(1):235\u20137. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/619416/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38093"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationM